cords, court documents, slave narratives, archaeological findings, and the memory of the African-American community, Clarke brings to light the long-suppressed history of the slaves of the Jones plantations-a history inseparably bound to that of their white owners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxBiographyxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aAfrican AmericanszGeorgiazLiberty CountyvBiography. 0aPlantation lifexHistoryx19th centuryxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aPlantation lifezGeorgiazLiberty CountyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPlantation ownersxBiographyxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aPlantation ownerszGeorgiazLiberty CountyvBiography. 0aSlavesxBiographyxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aSlaveszGeorgiazLiberty CountyvBiography. 0aWhite peoplezGeorgiazLiberty CountyvBiography. 0aWhitesxBiographyxGeorgiaxLiberty County. 0aWhiteszGeorgiazLiberty CountyvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030013328840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300133288/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles